R Fundamentals Part4-6: what is R markdown?

D-Lab

March 25, 2019

1 R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document.

2 Why use R Markdown?

R Markdown allows you create documents of various kinds. Check out the R Markdown Quick Tour. Some highlights:

  1. Enter text as normal. No special formatting is required for regular text.

  2. Code should be entered inside chunks that look like this:

2 + 2 # hashtag text within a chunk to comment it.
## [1] 4
# click "Code" and "Insert chunk" to see the keyboard shortcut.  

data(iris); summary(iris)
##   Sepal.Length    Sepal.Width     Petal.Length    Petal.Width   
##  Min.   :4.300   Min.   :2.000   Min.   :1.000   Min.   :0.100  
##  1st Qu.:5.100   1st Qu.:2.800   1st Qu.:1.600   1st Qu.:0.300  
##  Median :5.800   Median :3.000   Median :4.350   Median :1.300  
##  Mean   :5.843   Mean   :3.057   Mean   :3.758   Mean   :1.199  
##  3rd Qu.:6.400   3rd Qu.:3.300   3rd Qu.:5.100   3rd Qu.:1.800  
##  Max.   :7.900   Max.   :4.400   Max.   :6.900   Max.   :2.500  
##        Species  
##  setosa    :50  
##  versicolor:50  
##  virginica :50  
##                 
##                 
##

  1. Run a line of code like normal - remember you can select multiple lines to run at once.

  2. Click the green Play button on the right side of a chunk to run the entire chunk.

  3. Click the Run button (top right portion of your R Markdown window) to see various run options.

  4. Click Tools > Global options > Code and make sure the box is checked that says soft wrap R source files.

  5. Click Tools > Global options > Appearance to change your color and font settings.

  6. Click Tools > Global options > R Markdown and make sure to uncheck the box Show output inline for all R Markdown documents and check the box that says Show document outline by default. Also click Code > Show document outline to include a clickable table of contents in your RStudio session.

  7. Use knitr to generate .HTML, .docx, .pdf files, slideshows, and fancy applications. Click here and here for walkthroughs and examples.

  8. You can also embed plots, for example:

heart = read.csv("/Users/evan.admin/Desktop/R-Fundamentals/data-raw/heart.csv")

# For sex column, recode 0 = Female, 1 = Male
heart$sex_fac = ifelse(heart$sex == 0, "Female", "Male")

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = heart, aes(x = age, y = chol, col = sex_fac)) + 
  geom_point(size = 4, alpha = 0.5) + 
  ggtitle("Cholestorol versus age") + 
  xlab("Age (years)") + 
  ylab("Serum cholestorol (mg/dl)") +
  labs(col = "Sex") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue")) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

  1. Include statistical tests as well:
cor.test(heart$age, heart$chol)
